{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626561"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:39:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:39:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17080"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17080"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.07,0.43,0.33,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9770"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77843"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9770"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17080"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63360"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5254"},{"type":"tags","id":"5258"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22948"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23175"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26656"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77843"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old woman is admitted with methicillin-resistant \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E bacteraemia. She is commenced on intravenous vancomycin, a glycopeptide antibiotic.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of this type of antibiotic?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Interferes with bacterial folate synthesis","Blocks bacterial DNA gyrase enzyme","Binds to peptidoglycan precursors","Disrupts bacterial cell membrane integrity","Inhibits bacterial protein synthesis at the 50S ribosomal subunit"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGlycopeptide antibiotics such as vancomycin and teicoplanin work by \u003Cstrong\u003Ebinding to peptidoglycan precursors \u003C/strong\u003Eand prevents cell wall synthesis. Specifically, they bind to the D-alanyl-D-alanine terminus of peptidoglycan precursors, preventing cross-linking of the bacterial cell wall.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterferes with bacterial folate synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E - This mechanism belongs to sulfonamides and trimethoprim, which act by disrupting bacterial folic acid metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks bacterial DNA gyrase enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E - This is characteristic of fluoroquinolone antibiotics, which inhibit bacterial DNA replication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisrupts bacterial cell membrane integrity\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the action of polymyxins and daptomycin, which target the bacterial cell membrane.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits bacterial protein synthesis at the 50S ribosomal subunit\u003C/strong\u003E - This mechanism is utilised by macrolides and lincosamides, which prevent protein synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGlycopeptides are particularly useful against Gram-positive bacteria like \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EEnterococcus\u003C/em\u003E species. They cannot penetrate the outer membrane of Gram-negative bacteria, making them ineffective against these organisms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Glycopeptide antibiotics work by binding to peptidoglycan precursors and preventing bacterial cell wall synthesis.","Vancomycin and teicoplanin are the main glycopeptide antibiotics used clinically.","Glycopeptides are effective against Gram-positive bacteria but cannot penetrate the outer membrane of Gram-negative bacteria."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63360"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17080"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63360"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T17:24:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T17:24:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9770"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77843"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"ta